strategy:
1. I refuse any that have a noise pollution of above Moderate. Noise pollution is the worst.
2. If noise pollution is about the same, then I look at school.
3. If houses still equal, then I look at year of house. Houses built before the 1970s tend to be made of better materials. Or, go with the houses built in the 2000s.

In general, everything else can be fixed with money (ie. adding skylights for more natural light, kitchen reno). But you can't fix noise pollution or school district.
metastrategy: I had a simple strategy of going by one issue, but if that issue was close, looking at second issue, but if that issue was close, using a third issue to make the decision.

strategy:
I was trying to minimize the number of categories with very bad ratings.  
If the noise pollution was "very high", that was unacceptable, so I chose the other home.
If both the kitchen and the AC/Heating had bad ratings, I chose the other home.
If a home was small, with a small yard, those were both OK.
If the traffic was bad, that was tolerable, as long as most of the other ratings for the home were positive.
I tried to avoid the homes with "very bad" schools, but I did choose some, if most of the other ratings were positive.
The distances to parks, restaurants, etc. were not very important, as it would just take a little more time to get them if they were farther away.
metastrategy: I was careful and methodical in making my choices in Section 1, and I was aware of what the most important factors for each home were.  Since I was aware of how and why I was making my decisions, it made it fairly easy to answer the questions in Section 2, since my thought processes were still clear in my mind.
meditation_exp3: Daily or almost daily,5-15 minutes per day,5+ years
